As for your test code, it also does not make sense because you instantiate `DataService mockObj` as a local variable in your feature method (test method), which means that in your helper method `mockObj` cannot be accessed. So either you need to pass the object as a parameter to the helper methods or you need to make it a field in your test class.

Last, but not least, your local mock object is never injected into the class under test because, as I said in the first paragraph, the `DataService` object in `getData()` is also a local variable. Unless your application code is compeletely fake, there is no way to inject the mock because `getData()` does not have any method parameter and the `DataService` object is not a field which could be set via setter method or constructor. Thus, you can create as many mocks as you want, the application will never have any knowledge of them. So your stubbing `findByOffset(long offset)` (why don&#39;t you show the code of that method?) has no effect whatsoever.

